In general, <strong>Inequality</strong> is a statement indicating that two quantities are not equal.
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h2 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Inequality Symbols/Signs</h2>
</div>

<strong>Inequality symbols</strong> are symbols that tell us that quantities are not equal. They are;
<br>
  >  ≡ <strong>Greater than;</strong> < ≡ <strong>Less than;</strong>  ≥ ≡ <strong>Greater than or equal to;</strong>  ≤ ≡ <strong>Less than or equal to;</strong>  ≠ ≡ <strong>Not equal to (unequal).</strong>
  <br>
<strong>Algebraic inequality</strong> is an algebraic statement containing one or more inequality signs.
<br>
<strong>Note;</strong> ≥ also means <strong> ‘Not less than’</strong> while ≤ also means <strong> ‘Not greater than’</strong>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example 1</strong>
<br>
For each of these statements write an inequality statement in terms of the unknown;
<br>
(i)	The height of a tower h in metres is less than 10metres.
<br>
(ii)	Owen has $x. He spent $100. The amount he has left with him is greater than $25.
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
(i)	h < 10
<br>
(ii)x – 100 > 25
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example 2</strong>
<br>
The area of a square is less than 16m<sup>2</sup>. Use inequality statement to express the following;
<br>
(i)	The length of one of its sides.
<br>
(ii) The perimeter.
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
<div class="container">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col border-right border-danger">
    (i)
    <br>
    Let the <strong> length </strong>of a side of the square = y
    <br>
    The area of the square = 16m<sup>2</sup>
    <br>
    Area of a square = length x length
    <br>
    <strong>Area < length x length (with inequality sign <)</strong>
    <br>
     y x y < 16
     <br>
    y<sup>2</sup> < 16
    <br>
    y<sup>2</sup> < √16
    <br>
    y < 4 (therefore; length is less than 4m)
    </div>
    <div class="col">
    (ii)
    <br>	
    <strong>Let perimeter = p</strong>
    <br>
    Perimeter (p) of a square = 4length
    <br>
    y = 4m
    <br>
    p < 4y
    <br>
    p < 4 x 4
    <br>
    p < <strong>16m<sup>2</sup></strong>
    <br>
    Therefore; y < <strong>4m</strong> and p < <strong>16m<sup>2</sup></strong>
    </div>
  </div>
  </div>
<br>
<strong>Example 3</strong>
<br>
A pen costs $3 each. John has $x. It is not enough to buy a pen. Smith has $y. He is able to buy a pen. What can you say about the value of x and y?
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
 John’s money ($x) is less than $3. It means <strong>x < 3</strong> 
 <br>
Smith’s money ($y) is greater than $3. It means <strong>y > 3 </strong>
<br>
If Smith gets no balance amount (change) after the purchase, then <strong>y = 3</strong>
<br>
If he gets balance amount (change) after the purchase, then <strong>y > 3</strong>
<br>
But we do not know if smith gets balance amount (change) or not; then <strong>y ≥ 3</strong>
<br>
So; <strong>x < 3 and y ≥ 3</strong>
