In the algebraic inequality, when <strong>multiplying</strong> or <strong>dividing</strong> both sides of an inequality by a negative number, reverse the inequality sign to keep the statement true.
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example 1</strong>
<br>
Find the value of x that will satisfy the following inequalities;
<br>
(i) x + 3 < 7 (ii) 8 < 2x + 1 (iii) ─ 9 < 3x (iv) 18  ≥ ─3 ─3x (v) −4 –x ≤8 (vi) 4 ─ 3x ≤ ─11
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
<div class="container">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col border-right border-danger">
    (i)	
    <br>
    x + 3 < 7
    <br>
    x < 7 + 3
    <br>
    x < <strong>10</strong>
    </div>
    <div class="col">
    (ii)
    <br>
    8 < 2x + 1
    <br>
    8 ─ 1 < 2x
    <br>
    7  < 2x   ≡  2x  >  7
    <br>
    2x  >  7 divide both sides by 2
    <br>
    <sup>2x</sup>&frasl;<sub>x</sub>  >  <sup>7</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub>
    <br>
    x > <strong>3<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub></strong>
    </div>
  </div>
  </div>
<br>
<div class="container">
